    <item>
      <title>Development of a biodiversity index for residential towns</title>
      <link>https://xp-song.github.io/project/birt/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 01 Jun 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://xp-song.github.io/project/birt/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The rapid growth of urban areas worldwide exposes wildlife to new man-made stresses, and is a selective force that can drastically change the composition of animal communities. Understanding and measuring the impacts of the built environment on biodiversity are becoming increasingly important.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Environmental metrics or indices can be a useful tool to evaluate the effectiveness of actions aimed at mitigating biodiversity loss or promoting biodiversity conservation. 
&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/new-biodiversity-impact-assessment-guidelines-introduced-as-part-of-eia-review&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Environmental impact assessments&lt;/a&gt; are commonly used to measure the impact of new developments, and serve to protect biodiversity through legislation and guidelines. However, these assessments often rely on raw occurrence records that only provide information where a species has been detected, at a spatial scale that tends to be too coarse for use in urban design and planning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This project aims to develop a probabilistic index of biodiversity, based on an understanding of how landscape components impact four animal groups—birds, butterflies, odonates and amphibians. Remotely sensed (e.g. satellite imagery, LiDAR) and open-source data are used to streamline data collection and generalise findings across the wider landscape. The efficacy of various national policy tools (e.g. Green Plot Ratio) in enriching wildlife will also be assessed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The project is funded from 2016–2022 by the Singapore Housing Development Board ($1,286,980), awarded to the National University of Singapore. The lead principal investigator is Dr. Chong Kwek Yan. We are looking to hire a Research Assistant starting Q2 2021, and offer 
&lt;a href=&#34;https://kwekings.wordpress.com/about-me/about/student-projects-on-offer/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;student projects&lt;/a&gt; as well. We appreciate enquiries and would like to hear about your specific interest in our work.&lt;/p&gt;















